en: 07   Noli me Tangere, c.1514 (NG270)

Volume 34 of the National Gallery Technical Bulletin is dedicated to the evolution of Titian’s technique in the first part of his career, up to around 1540. This volume presents catalogue entries for 13 by Titian, four of which do not belong to the National Gallery (cats 1, 2, 3, and 13). At this time it is not possible to include extra images for those four catalogue entries.
  • 01 The Flight into Egypt, c.1507. The State Hermitage Museum, St Petersburg: For further information about this picture see https://www.hermitagemuseum.org (Accessed Feb 2022)
  • 02 Christ and the Adulteress and Head of a Man, c.1508-10. Glasgow Museums: For further information about this picture see http://collections.glasgowmuseums.com (Accessed Feb 2022)
  • 03 Rest on the Flight into Egypt, c.1508-9. The Most Hon. the Marquess of Bath, Longleat House, Warminster, Wiltshire.: At this time no further information is available for this painting.

NG270: Titian, Noli me Tangere, paint cross-section from the brown leaves visible at the bottom of photomicrograph m016. The sample shows the gesso ground, the off-white imprimatura, the warm pinkish-grey of the clouds in the sky, the thin yellow-brown base colour of the tree, which can be distinguished in SEM images from the thick opaque greenish brown paint of the foliage above it. Orange-yellow and red earth are clearly visible, with dark agglomorates of indigo that appear black, as well as translucent particles of verdigris which appear brownish in the cross-section. The translucent dark brown layer at the surface comprises accumulated dirt and remnants of a degraded surface coating. (2016x4164px)
